{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01UernVRc9E2KK3nBQtMX23R","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. The engineering task is complete. `output/calculation_note.md` exists and reports all six required quantities, each with assumptions and a confidence level, and states explicitly that every number was derived from physics and the given inputs without consulting the facility's published data.\n\n## What I built\n\nA coupled first-principles model (`rccs_model.py`, `rccs_cases.py`, `rccs_sensitivity.py`) solving four physics sub-models to a self-consistent steady state — buoyancy-loop momentum balance (mass flow), air energy balance (ΔT), internal duct convection (wall T), and cavity radiation + natural convection (plate T and the rad/conv split) — plus a decay-heat transient and a weather sweep. Air properties from CoolProp; correlations from general literature (Gnielinski, MacGregor–Emery, Haaland, Idelchik/Crane, gray-surface radiation exchange), all cited.\n\n## Headline predictions (56 kW cavity duty, inlet 20 °C)\n\n1. **Mass flow:** 0.55 kg/s ≈ 33 kg/min *(moderate, ±25%)*\n2. **Riser air rise:** ~100 K (20 → 121 °C) *(moderate)*\n3. **Riser wall (front face, z=3500 mm):** ~170 °C; **plate/vessel:** ~375 °C *(good)*\n4. **Radiation/convection split:** ~91% radiation / 9% cavity convection *(high confidence — robust to ε)*\n5. **Accident case:** peak plate ~375 °C at t≈85 h; **self-limiting — levels off, does not run away** (T⁴ radiation + flow both rise with temperature → stable equilibrium), staying ~125 °C below a conservative ~500 °C steel limit *(safe, with margin)*\n6. **Weather:** colder air → ~+18% more flow and lower wall temps; plate/vessel temperature nearly insensitive (radiation-set); wind dynamic pressure (~78 Pa at 11 m/s) is comparable to the ~50 Pa draft so it perturbs flow direction-dependently but is buffered by the flow conditioner/dampers.\n\n**Most uncertain assumption:** the fraction of the 82 kWe input that actually reaches the risers (assumed 56 kW / ~32% parasitic); sensitivity to it, to riser emissivity, and to loop form-loss coefficients is quantified in §6–7. A results figure is saved to `output/rccs_results.png`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1020,"cache_read_input_tokens":82826,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1020},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a52b4a50-76e4-4bf5-8639-5052ad16c2ae","uuid":"3fdc2f15-c1ae-4c8a-bfde-1a075f216031","request_id":"req_011Cccu1d4KNX88HRkjT8JxD"}
